Certainly! Here’s how to initialize Cardboard.js and append a simple `div` containing a `p` element with the text 'Hello world!':

javascript
import { tag, init, allTags } from '@nkeff/cardboard-js';

const { div, p } = allTags;

// Initialize Cardboard.js (defaults to <body>)
const root = init();

// Append a div with a paragraph
root.append(
  div(
    p('Hello world!')
  )
);

This code dynamically generates and attaches the DOM elements without requiring any HTML template files.

Here’s a complete component that toggles a button’s state and background color reactively:

javascript
import { tag, state, button } from '@nkeff/cardboard-js';

const ToggleButton = () => {
  const isOn = state(false);

  return button()
    .text(isOn.map(on => on ? 'ON' : 'OFF'))
    .styles({
      backgroundColor: isOn.map(on => on ? 'green' : 'gray'),
      padding: '10px 20px',
      border: 'none',
      borderRadius: '5px',
      color: 'white',
      cursor: 'pointer'
    })
    .clicked(() => isOn.value = !isOn.value);
};

// Mount the component to the body
tag('(body)').append(ToggleButton());

The button’s text and background color update automatically when `isOn` changes, thanks to Cardboard’s reactive state system.
